                Repurchase Agreements (REPO) &
                Liquidity Management
            </p>

            <div style="font-family:calibri;text-align: justify; font-size:16px; margin: 2px 21px;">
                A repurchase, or repo, agreement (short for sale and repurchase) involves an institution with a
                liquidity need selling a perceived liquid security for cash for a price x and agreeing to buy it back at a
                later date for a price greater than x. The difference between the two prices represents the interest
                payment relating to period for which the underlying security was ‘sold’ for cash. In other words, this
                is nothing but borrowing short term funds pledging a specified liquid asset as collateral. The market
                is burgeoning: it is estimated that the overall size in repo agreements would exceed USD 15 trillion
                by 2020.<br /><br />
                To borrow in the repo market, banks must have underlying, liquid, assets, to pledge against the
                borrowing —collateral, in other words. It is the supply of, and demand for, collateral that determines
                liquidity in the financial markets. However, not all collateral can be treated equally. Counterparties
                taking possession of the underlying collateral assume credit risk, i.e., the possibility that the
                borrower fails to repay, and the securities they are left holding may not sell for their face value.<br /><br />
                Therefore, they apply a discount, or “haircut”, to the collateral, depending on its perceived riskiness.
                At times of stress, lenders get more nervous and factor in bigger discounts than during times of
                normalcy, and this, in a nutshell, is what happened during the financial crisis. Bigger haircuts mean
                that borrowers need more collateral than before in order to fund themselves. When market
                volatility spikes, funding capacity drops in tandem and often exponentially. The result, a liquidity
                squeeze at the worst possible moment, is a template of how the next crisis may occur, although
                regulators are trying to reduce institutions’ reliance on short-term funding. This though, is easier
                said than done, since the Central Banks do not have access to the members’ daily position profiles.
                Just as there are participants in the market in need of liquidity, there will be players who have
                surplus liquidity in need of yield enhancement, and they seek avenues to lend, and they may buy an
                identified liquid security for cash, and then sell it back at a later date. These are called a ‘reverse’
                repos and these transactions take the facet of ‘buy and sell back’. A repo for one counterparty is
                simply a reverse repo for the other.
